1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 d6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. h3 ({If White
decides not to spend time on h2-h3, then the resulting positions are rather
dry, both sides do not have big chances for a win...} 7. Bd3 e6 8. O-O exd5 9.
exd5 ({Worse is} 9. cxd5 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nbd7 {In Modern Benoni
structures exchange of white-squared bishop is almost always favourable for
Black.}) 9... Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nfd7 12. Qd1 f5 13. f4 Na6 14. Bd2 Nc7
15. Qf3 Qh4 16. Kh2 Rae8 17. g3 Qd8 18. Rae1 h5 19. Kg2 Nf6 20. Bc2 a6 21. a4
b6 $11 {1/2 (49) Mrva,M (2445)-Chatalbashev,B (2535) Krynica 1998}) 7... e6 8.
Bd3 Na6 {The key move, that I like the most. Black's idea is, after the knight
comes to c7, to threat taking on d5 and no matter how White responds- exd5 or
cxd5 - answer it with b7-b5. And if White decides not to allow this and play
a2-a4, then we close the position with e6-e5, receiving a favourable kind of
King's Indian. In that case, yes, we have lost a tempo, but typical White's
play on the queenside with a3 and b4 is impossible. Obviously in such
positions a2-a4 is not a good move, the square b4 might be of some use for
Black later.} ({The reason this is the main line against Black's set-up goes
back to the huge influence to the game Botvinnik had in his time (and not
only!) - he proved that} 8... exd5 9. exd5 Re8+ 10. Be3 Bh6 11. O-O $1 {
favours White.}) 9. O-O {The most natural move and as it is so often in chess,
probably the best one also.} ({Some years ago} 9. Bg5 {was considered
dangerous for Black. Not any more, because of the pawn sacrifice typical for
many Benoni positions - b7-b5! Here it is surely justified, as White has not
castled yet. It is a semi-forced line though, so it requires some memory. The
good thing - it is the only such line, all others can be handled just by
intuition and understanding.} h6 10. Be3 exd5 11. exd5 (11. cxd5 b5 $1 {Safer
is} 12. Nxb5 (12. O-O c4 13. Bc2 b4 14. Nb5 Re8 15. Nd2 Nc5 16. Nxc4 Nfxe4 17.
Bxe4 Nxe4 $13 18. Nxa7 $5 {with huge complications} Ba6 (18... Rxa7 {might be
best} 19. Bxa7 Qc7 20. Qc2 (20. Qa4 Re7 21. Nb6 Bf5 $13) 20... Qxa7 21. Rae1
Bf5 (21... Qe7 22. Qxe4 Qxe4 23. Rxe4 Rxe4 24. Nxd6 Re2 $11) 22. g4 Qe7 23.
gxf5 Qg5+ 24. Kh2 Qf4+ $11) 19. Nc6 Qh4 20. Rc1 $2 (20. Nb6 $1 $14) 20... Nc3
$1 21. bxc3 Bxc4 22. cxb4 Rxa2 23. Rc2 Ra1 24. Rc1 Rxc1 25. Qxc1 Bxf1 26. Qxf1
Qe4 {0-1 (27) Blagojevic,D (2528)-Chatalbashev,B (2561) Zagreb 2010}) 12... Nb4
13. O-O Ba6 14. Bc4 Nxe4 15. a3 Qb6 16. axb4 Bxb5 17. bxc5 Nxc5 18. Bxb5 Qxb5 {
1/2 (18) Borovikov,V (2585)-Chatalbashev,B (2561) Bad Liebenzell 2010}) 11...
Nb4 12. Bb1 b5 $1 13. a3 (13. Nxb5 Ba6 14. O-O Nfxd5 $15) 13... Qa5 14. O-O
bxc4 15. Qd2 Nd3 16. Bxh6 Rb8 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Bxd3 cxd3 19. b4 Qa6 (19... Qc7
$5 20. Qxd3 cxb4 21. axb4 Rxb4 22. Rfc1 Qb6 $11) 20. b5 Qa5 21. Qxd3 Bf5 22.
Qd2 Rfe8 23. Rfc1 {White is slightly better, but the max. he can achieve is
some ending 3 against 2 pawns on the kingside. Trying for more might result in}
a6 24. a4 Qb4 25. bxa6 Ne4 26. Nxe4 Bxe4 27. a7 Rb7 28. Qxb4 Rxb4 29. Ng5 Bd3
30. Ra3 c4 31. Nf3 Ra8 32. Nd4 Rxa7 33. Rca1 (33. a5) 33... Ra6 34. f3 Kf6 35.
Nb5 (35. Nc6) 35... Ke5 36. Kf2 Rb2+ 37. Kg3 Ra5 38. Nc3 Kd4 $17 {0-1 (124)
Georgiev,K (2671)-Ivanisevic,I (2664) Subotica 2008 CBM 126 Extra [Boris
Chatalbashev]}) (9. a3 {is harmless} exd5 10. cxd5 Re8 11. O-O c4 12. Bc2 Nc5
13. Re1 b5 14. Bf4 Bb7 15. Nd4 Qb6 16. Nc6 Bxc6 17. dxc6 Re6 18. b4 cxb3 (18...
Na6 $5) 19. Bxb3 Nxb3 20. Qxb3 Qxc6 21. Rac1 Qe8 22. Qxb5 Qxb5 23. Nxb5 Rxe4
$11 {1/2 (70) Georgiev,K (2669)-Chatalbashev,B (2555) Blagoevgrad 2010}) (9.
dxe6 {is rarely played in that position. Black has weak pawn on d6, but d4
square is also weak. The knight maneuvers Nb4-c6 and Nd7-e5 are typical ways
of trying to expoit it.} Bxe6 10. O-O Nd7 (10... Nb4 11. Be2 Nc6 12. Bf4 Nd4 {
or Qb6 and Nd4}) 11. Bg5 Bf6 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Qd2 Nb4 14. Ng5 $2 (14. Be2 Ne5
15. Nxe5 Bxe5) 14... Nxd3 15. Nxe6 Rxe6 16. Qxd3 g5 $17 {0-1 (52) Odendahl,S 
(2400)-Quinteros,M (2515) Lone Pine 1980}) 9... Nc7 {Black is ready to take on
d5 with b7-b5 next. White has a big choice now - he may take on e6, he may
prevent the threat by playing a2-a4 or ignore it. In the last case it is also
a big question how he will take on d5 - ed5 or cd5. As you will see in the
game section, many prefer to take the decision now - according to the type of
positions they like. But the best move is to postpone it and play} 10. Re1 {
first, protecting e4 pawn - 10...ed5 11.cd5 b5? is not working immediately for
Black as after 12.Nxb5 Nxb5 13.Bxb5 he can not take on e4.} Re8 {The idea is
clear - to put pressure on e4 pawn. Generally this is all the theory we need
to know. From now on both sides usually have huge choice of moves, which is
normal - note that not a single pawn is exchanged yet! And the most important
thing here are the plans and ideas - let's see how they are handled in
practice.} ({Another way of supporting b7-b5 is} 10... Rb8 {Here in case of
the most common reaction - 11.a4 after 11...e5, Black's other rook is better
placed on f8, rather than on e8. Because sooner or later f7-f5 will follow,
the typical way for playing King's Indian - starting the attack on the
kingside. But in the plan with ignoring b7-b5,  10...Re8 is more useful than
10...Rb8. So, it is really a subtle thing, that will hardly decide the game,
but which of the two moves is better? Practical advice - when preparing for a
certain opponent, it is good to take a notice not only which moves he likes in
the opening, but also about his favourite type of positions. That way you may
guess his next move(s) and make a choice accordingly.}) *

