{Chapter 1A : Plan with a2-a4} 10. a4 ({Some other good examples of typical
King's Indian play. In this opening engines quite often estimate the positions
in White's favour. But you should not be bothered, Nakamura once said that
computers really understand nothing about King's Indian! And it is true!} 10.
Re1 Rb8 11. a4 e5 12. Bg5 (12. a5 Nfe8 13. Bd2 f5 14. Qb1 f4 15. Be2 g5 16. Nh2
Nf6 17. Qd1 Rf7 18. Ng4 Nce8 19. f3 h5 20. Nf2 Bf8 21. b4 cxb4 22. Na2 Qxa5 23.
Nxb4 Qd8 24. Rxa7 g4 25. fxg4 hxg4 26. Bxg4 Nxg4 27. hxg4 Rg7 28. Qb3 Bxg4 29.
c5 Qh4 30. c6 f3 31. Nh1 Rh7 {0-1 (31) Lputian,S (2540)-Milos,G (2510) Palma
de Mallorca 1989}) 12... h6 13. Be3 Kh8 14. Qd2 Ng8 15. Nh2 f5 16. exf5 gxf5
17. f4 Na6 18. Kh1 b6 19. Rad1 Nb4 20. Bb1 Rb7 21. Rg1 Rbf7 22. Rdf1 Bd7 23.
Rf2 Qh4 24. Nb5 Qe7 25. Rgf1 a6 26. Nc3 Qh4 $6 (26... e4 $142) 27. Nf3 (27.
fxe5 $1 dxe5 28. a5 f4 29. Qe2 $1) 27... Qe7 28. g3 e4 29. Nh4 Qf6 30. Qd1 Re7
31. Ng2 Qg6 32. g4 fxg4 33. f5 Bxf5 34. Nf4 Qe8 35. hxg4 Bd7 36. Rh2 Nf6 37.
Rg1 Nh7 38. Nh5 Be5 39. Rh3 Rf3 40. Rxf3 exf3 41. Bxh6 Bxg4 42. Nf4 Bxf4 43.
Bxf4 Qh5+ 44. Bh2 f2 {0-1 (44) Lazarev,V (2450)-Chatalbashev,B (2535) Bourbon
Lancy 1998}) 10... Na6 11. Be3 e5 12. Kh2 Nb4 13. Be2 Nh5 14. g3 f5 15. exf5
Bxf5 {Generally, in similar positions, it is preferable to take with a pawn.
But in our variation with the knight already on b4, taking with the bishop
gives some tactical ideas. Here Black was not afraid that he might lose a
piece, with such an activity it is logical there is some tactical resource in
his favour!} 16. g4 $6 Bc2 $1 17. Qd2 Nf4 18. Ne1 Qh4 19. Bxf4 Rxf4 20. Nxc2
Bh6 $1 21. Bd1 Rf3 22. Bxf3 Bxd2 {...} 0-1

