{The same structure arised in my game against the strong grandmaster Dmitri
Tyomkin.  Diagram [#]  In the position on the diagram, White played} 10. a4 {
which was met by} e5 {In this game, I have decided to adopt the plan we are
already familiar with: when White plays a2-a4, we close the center by means of
e6-e5 followed by the maneuver Na6-b4,} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Be3 Na6 $5 $146 {Even
though Black's last move looks logical, we must admit that it has some obvious
drawbacks. Firstly, in order to reach "b4" square, black knight loses two
tempi which are important, despite the closed character of the position.
Moreover, is some positions, if it's not supported by other pieces, the knight
will remain out of play.} ({Some grandmasters prefer to launch an attack on
the kingside, without losing any additional time. For example, in one of his
games, the Israeli GM Ilia Smirin gave preference to the move} 12... Nh5 13.
Qd2 Kh7 14. a5 Na6 15. g4 $6 Qf6 $1 $15 {White has no compensation for the
weakened kingside. 0-1 Porper,E-Smirin,I/Israel 1996/CBM 52 ext (61)}) 13. Rc1
{[%cal Yd3b1] White intends to meet the move Nb4 by Bb1. Otherwise, his rook
on "a1" will remain out of play.} Nb4 14. Bb1 b6 15. Qd2 Kh7 16. Kh2 {[%cal
Gf3g1,Gg1e2] /\Ng1-e2} a6 17. Ng1 Nh5 18. g3 $6 {White is weakening his
kingside without any particular reason. It's interesting to mention that in
his comments to the game, Tyomkin explains the result of the current game by
his insufficient understanding on that kind of positions. Such a comment
perfectly illustrates the practical value of our weapon.} f5 19. exf5 (19. Nge2
$2 f4 {[%csl Re3][%cal Yg7e5]}) 19... Bxf5 {Maybe the reader has already
noticed that in such kind of positions, I am inclined to take on "f5" with the
bishop. In this case, I decided to play in this way, in order to eliminate the
dangerous opposition along "b1-h7" diagonal.} (19... gxf5 20. Nge2 (20. g4 Nf6
$132)) 20. Ne4 $6 {This is already a dubious move. White hasn't enough
ressources to keep the control over "e4" square.} (20. Bxf5 gxf5 {[%cal Gf2f4]
/\f4}) (20. f3 $5 $11) 20... Nf6 21. f3 ({Exchanges don't help White too. After
} 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Ne2 Bxb1 23. Rxb1 Qf3 $17 {[%csl Re4,Rf3,Rg2] Black has
the initiative because of the weakened light-squares in White's camp.}) 21...
Nxe4 $1 22. Bxe4 (22. fxe4 Bd7 23. b3 b5 $17 {[%csl Rb1,Rc4]}) 22... Qd7 23. b3
b5 $17 {After this typical pawn break, Black has overwhelming initiative. He
is planing to open "b" file and activate his queen's rook. White's position is
already very difficult.} 24. axb5 axb5 25. Ra1 bxc4 26. bxc4 Ra4 27. Rfb1 Rfa8
28. Qd1 {Diagram [#]  In this position, Black is winning by using a small
tactical operation. letting black to gain a pawn c4 by small tactical
operation.} Bxe4 29. fxe4 Nc2 $1 $19 30. Rxa4 Qxa4 31. Bf2 Qxc4 {...} 0-1

