{Chapter 1C: White allows b7-b5. This is a dangerous option, especially if it
is followed by exd5 - as the game here shows. It is important to note the
set-up with Kh8, Ng8. The position is semi-closed and Black can afford to stay
passive for some moves before regrouping.} 10. Bg5 {The idea of White's 10.Bg5
is:after} h6 11. Be3 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gd1d2] and eventual Qd1-d2 Ph6 will be
attacked.} exd5 12. exd5 b5 13. b3 Re8 ({This regrouping of the pieces looks
better if we include} 13... b4 {first, so 14.a3 from the line above is not a
strong option.} 14. Ne2 Kh8 15. Qd2 Ng8 {Then apart from the standart
counterplay with a5-a4, Black may think also about Ne8-f6, Ra7. It is
important to know that f7-f5, gaining space on the kingside, is logical only
when White can not make a good use of e6 square, for example if his knight on
e2 has gone already to g3, or the bishop is on f4, preventing his own knight
to jump there. Generally yes, for the moment our position is little passive,
but White can hardly exploit the fact.}) 14. Qd2 Kh7 15. Rae1 b4 16. Ne2 Ne4
17. Qc2 f5 $2 {This is a serious mistake. Now Black's kingside is complitely
weakened.} 18. g4 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc2h7] Beautiful move! This move allows
White not only to create concrete threats on the kingside but also to make use
of the opposition along the "b1-h7" diagonal.} Qf6 19. Ng3 fxg4 (19... Nxg3 20.
fxg3 $16 {[%cal Gf1f6]}) 20. Nh2 $1 ({Badly is} 20. Nxe4 $2 {in view of} Qxf3 (
{or} 20... Rxe4 21. Bxe4 gxf3 22. Kh2 Qe5+ 23. Kg1 Qh5 $17) 21. Nxd6 gxh3 22.
Bxg6+ Kg8 $17) 20... Ng5 $6 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rc7,Rc8,Rh7]} 21. hxg4 Qf7 22. f4 {
White has converted his advantage without any difficulties.} 1-0

[Event "Split op 1st"]
[Site "Split"]
