{Chapter II: System with 7.Be2, Averbakh, Four Pawns' Attack, Fianchetto,
Saemisch, System with 6.Bd3 and 7.Nge2  Apart from the main line, White has
several other ways of development. Most often these variations are connected
with the theory of King's Indian or Modern Benoni. Of course, I can not cover
in this article every line from the other openings. But as I have quite a lot
of practice here, I shall give you just my opinion about the best options for
Black. And there are also some interesting independant possibilities.} 1. d4 g6
2. c4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. e4 e6 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Be2 {This variation is
second best in popularity.} O-O 8. O-O exd5 ({The difference between} 8... Re8
{and the text is that the subtle rook move discourages 9.Nd2, compared to 8...
exd5 9.cxd5 Re8 10.Nd2. Without the exchange on d5, white knight can not jump
on c4 - an excellent square in all kinds of Modern Benoni positions. So after
8...Re8 9.Nd2 Black can continue with Na6-c7, leaving exd5 for better times.} {
Though White's play is far from perfect, the following game is a good example
- Black manages to get into life all the typical ideas in positions with this
pawn structure.} 9. Bg5 ({With this move order Black allows} 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10.
Bf4 {but it is hardly something to be afraid of. We have already seen similar
positions in the main line, d4 square is enough compensation for the weak pawn
on d6. For example} Bg4 (10... Qb6 11. Qc2 (11. Bxd6 Rd8 12. e5 Ne8) 11... Nc6
12. Rad1 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bf5 14. Nfd2 Nd4 15. Qd3 Bxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 f5
18. Rxd6 Rxe4 19. Rxb6 Rxe2 20. Rxb7 Bxb2 $11 {1/2 (26) Hulak,K (2505)
-Gheorghiu,F (2525) New York 1986}) 11. Qd3 (11. h3 Nxe4 $1 12. hxg4 (12. Nxe4
Rxe4 13. Bg5 Qe8 14. Bd3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Re6 16. Qxb7 Nc6 17. Bc2 Rb8 18. Qc7 Rc8
(18... Rxb2 19. Ba4 Rb6 $15) 19. Qb7 h6 20. Bh4 (20. Be3 $15) 20... Re2 21.
Rac1 Rb8 22. Qc7 Bxb2 (22... Rxb2 23. Ba4 Qe4 $17) 23. Bd3 Bxc1 $6 24. Bxe2 Bf4
25. Bf3 Nd4 26. Bd5 $44 {1-0 (49) Farago,I (2477)-Ivanisevic,I (2638) Hungary
2013}) 12... Bxc3 13. Qb3 Bg7 14. Rae1 Qd7 15. g5 Nc6 16. Bd3 f5 17. gxf6 Nxf6
$15 {0-1 (47) Zilka,S (2525)-Kislinsky,A (2574) Ledec nad Sazavou 2013}) 11...
Nc6 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Ne5 (13... Nd7 $11) 14. Qe2 Qb6 15. Rad1 h6 (15... Re6
$11) 16. Rd2 a6 17. Rfd1 {White has just a tiny edge...1-0 (47) Cori,J (2596)
-Hernandez Guerrero,G (2517) Buenos Aires ARG 2015}) 9... h6 10. Bd2 Na6 11. h3
exd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. g4 $6 Bd7 14. Re1 h5 15. Nh2 hxg4 16. hxg4 Ne4 17. Nxe4
Rxe4 18. Qc2 Rd4 $1 19. Be3 Qh4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. Bf3 Nb4 22. Qd2 Nd3 $1 $19 {
0-1 (40) Franic,M (2392)-Chatalbashev,B (2561) Zagreb 2010}) 9. exd5 ({More
challenging is} 9. cxd5 {where I like Cebalo's approach. I barely survived in
the following game.} Na6 10. Nd2 Nc7 11. a4 b6 12. Nc4 Ba6 {As we know, the
exchange of this bishop for a knight is always good in Benoni.} 13. Bf4 Bxc4
14. Bxc4 Nh5 15. Be3 Re8 16. Qd3 a6 17. Rab1 Qd7 {White must be always careful
with future b6-b5 and the decision to prevent it in a radical way does not
help much.} 18. b4 Bxc3 $1 19. Qxc3 Rxe4 20. bxc5 bxc5 21. Qc2 Rae8 22. Rb7 Nf4
23. g3 Qg4 24. Bxf4 Rxf4 25. Rc1 Re7 26. h3 Qg5 27. Qd2 Rf5 28. Qxg5 Rxg5 29.
Bxa6 Rxd5 30. Bf1 Rd4 31. a5 Ra4 32. a6 Kg7 33. a7 $2 (33. Rb6 Rd7 $11) 33...
Nd5 $17 {1/2 (37) Chatalbashev,B (2561)-Cebalo,M (2500) Zagreb 2010 CBM 145 
[Boris Chatalbashev]}) 9... Re8 10. h3 Na6 11. a3 (11. Bg5 h6 12. Be3 Bf5 13.
Qd2 Kh7 14. Nh2 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. a3 Nc7 17. Rae1 b5 18. Ng4 h5 19. Nh2 Rb8
20. Bg5 Qd7 21. b3 b4 (21... bxc4 $5 $15) 22. axb4 Rxb4 23. Bd1 (23. Bd3 $11)
23... a5 24. f3 Bb1 25. Rxe8 Nxe8 26. Re1 Bd4+ 27. Be3 Bxe3+ 28. Qxe3 Ng7 29.
Qc1 Qf5 $13 {0-1 (68) Petkov,V (2450)-Chatalbashev,B (2490) Plovdiv 2007})
11... Nc7 12. Rb1 Bf5 13. Bd3 Qd7 14. Bf4 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Re1 Bxd3 17.
Qxd3 b5 18. b4 bxc4 19. Qxc4 Nb5 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Rb3 Nd4 22. Nxd4 Bxd4 23.
bxc5 Bxc5 24. Be3 {Correct play from both sides and a logical result.} 1/2-1/2

