1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5 c5 7. d5 {In my
opinion, Averbakh variation against King's Indian is somewhat underestimated
these days. Though not very popular, we have to be ready to face it with our
system also, via different move order.} e6 ({White's idea is after} 7... h6 8.
Bf4 {to discourage} e6 {though it is still the main move, connected with a
pawn sacrifice on d6. But it is not what I consider best.}) 8. Qd2 {Now White
prevents h7-h6 in the future and the pin is a little bit unpleasant.} (8. Nf3 {
is not logical - after} h6 9. Be3 exd5 {this version of Benoni is good for
Black, for example} 10. cxd5 b5 $1 11. Bxb5 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Qa5+ 13. Nc3 Bxc3+
14. bxc3 Qxb5 15. Qb3 Ba6 16. Qxb5 Bxb5 17. Nd2 Bd3 18. Bxh6 Re8+ 19. Kd1 Nd7
20. Rc1 Nb6 21. Re1 Rxe1+ 22. Kxe1 Re8+ 23. Be3 f5 24. Nf3 f4 25. Kd2 c4 26.
Bxb6 Re2+ 27. Kd1 axb6 28. Rb1 Rxf2 29. Rxb6 Rxg2 30. Ke1 Re2+ 31. Kd1 Rxa2 {
0-1 (37) Donner,J (2470)-Portisch,L (2640) Lugano 1968}) 8... exd5 9. exd5 Qb6
{I like this move - now the knight on f6 is not pinned and we prepare the
standart Bf5-Ne4 which will put pressure on b2 pawn.} 10. Nf3 Bf5 11. Nh4 {The
only way to fight for an advantage. The complications are not so dangerous for
Black though.} Ne4 $1 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. f3 h6 $1 ({White is better after
immediate} 13... Qxb2 14. Rc1 {as Carlsen once proved against Van Wely.}) 14.
Bxh6 {If the bishop retreats, Black wiil take on b2 and play Qf6 next.} Bxh6
15. Qxh6 Qxb2 16. O-O Bc2 17. Kh1 (17. Rac1 Re8 18. Qd2 Qf6) (17. Qd2 Qd4+)
17... Re8 18. Qd2 Qd4 19. Qxc2 Qxh4 20. Rab1 b6 21. f4 Nd7 22. f5 Kg7 23. Rb3
Qe7 ({The position after} 23... Rh8 $1 24. Rh3 Qg5 {is approximately equal,
but easier to play with Black. He is safe from any trouble with such a nice
knight on e5.}) 24. Bd1 Qe4 $6 25. Qf2 $6 (25. Qc1 $1 $16) 25... Qd4 26. Qf3
Qf6 27. fxg6 fxg6 28. Qxf6+ Nxf6 $11 1-0

