{Four pawns' attack is not as dangerous here, especially compared to Modern
Benoni, where White has the possibility of early Bb5+. There are several
decent options for Black, but I like Radjabov's choice the most. In many lines
it is Black that may end on top after the opening!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4 c5 6. d5 e6 ({Most common move order is} 6... O-O 7. Nf3 e6
{Now} 8. dxe6 fxe6 9. Bd3 {is well-known that it gives White nothing -after
the following famous game by Kasparov.} Nc6 10. O-O Nd4 $1 11. Ng5 $5 (11. Ne2
$142) 11... e5 $1 (11... h6 12. Nf3 $1) 12. f5 h6 13. Nh3 gxf5 14. exf5 b5 $1
15. Be3 $2 (15. Nxb5 $142 $1 Nxb5 (15... e4 16. Be2 Nxf5 $10) 16. cxb5 d5 $13)
15... bxc4 16. Bxc4+ Kh8 {/\ 17.d5, >< Pf5} 17. Bxd4 cxd4 18. Nd5 $17 Ba6 $1
19. Nxf6 Bxc4 20. Nh5 Bxf1 21. Qg4 Qd7 22. Rxf1 d3 (22... Rac8 $17) 23. Qf3 d2
24. g4 (24. f6 Bxf6 $1 25. Nxf6 Qg7) 24... Rac8 $1 25. Qd3 Qa4 26. Nf2 Qd4 $1
$19 {0-1 (26) Christiansen,L (2575)-Kasparov,G (2675) Moscow 1982}) 7. Nf3 exd5
8. cxd5 O-O 9. Be2 Nbd7 {A rare move, which will most probably surprise your
opponent. And it is a good one too!} 10. Nd2 ({The development with} 10. O-O
Re8 11. Qc2 {is not better} Qe7 12. Re1 Nb6 $1 (12... Nxe4 13. Bd3 f5 14. Nxe4
fxe4 15. Rxe4 $14) 13. Bd2 Bd7 (13... Nxe4 $5) 14. Bf1 Bg4 15. Qd1 Nfd7 16. h3
Bxf3 17. Qxf3 c4 18. a4 Nc5 19. a5 Nb3 20. Rad1 $6 (20. axb6 $1 Nxd2 21. Qf2
Bxc3 (21... Nxf1 22. bxa7 $1 $14) 22. bxc3 Nxe4 23. Rxa7 $1 Rab8 24. Qd4 f5 25.
Bxc4 Qh4 $11) 20... Nxa5 21. Nb5 Qd7 22. Na3 Nb3 23. Nxc4 Nxd2 24. Rxd2 Nxc4
25. Bxc4 b5 26. Bd3 a5 27. Rde2 Rad8 28. Qf2 a4 $15 {0-1 (45) Banikas,H (2608)
-Radjabov,T (2733) Bursa 2010}) (10. e5 {is obviously premature} dxe5 11. fxe5
Ng4 12. e6 Nde5 $15) 10... Re8 11. O-O c4 $1 {A standart tactical resource in
Modern Benoni, exploiting both the diagonal g1-a7 and the vulnerability of e4
pawn. An important nuance is that the last move is better to be played
immediately, without including 11...a6 12.a4. Note that this position might
also happen with different move order - when White goes for the classical line
with 7.Be2 (see Evdokimov-Volokitin above) and later tries to stop black
knight from jumping on e5 - 11.f4.} 12. Kh1 ({Taking the pawn now gives Black
better chances -} 12. Bxc4 Nc5 13. e5 (13. Bb5 Re7 14. Re1 $2 Ng4 15. e5 Nd3 $1
$19) (13. Qc2 Ng4 14. Nf3 Qb6 15. Kh1 Bxc3 $17) 13... dxe5 14. fxe5 Rxe5 15.
Nf3 Re8 16. d6 Qb6 17. Kh1 Be6 $15) 12... Nc5 13. e5 (13. Bf3 b5 14. Nxb5 {is
playing with fire, Black gets enormous activity, threatening to win the game
in just a few moves -} Nfxe4 15. Nxc4 Rb8 16. Nd4 (16. Nba3 Ba6 $17) 16... Ba6
$19 17. b3 (17. Be2 Rb4) 17... Bxc4 18. bxc4 Nf2+ 19. Rxf2 Bxd4) 13... dxe5 14.
fxe5 Rxe5 15. Nxc4 Re8 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bxf6 ({With} 17. Bh4 Nce4 $1 18. Nxe4
Rxe4 19. Bg3 Qxd5 20. Qxd5 Nxd5 21. Bf3 Rd4 22. Rad1 Nb6 23. Rxd4 Bxd4 24. Rd1
Bf6 25. b3 Nxc4 26. bxc4 Kg7 27. h3 {White should be able to hold, but not
more.} a5 {1/2-1/2 (42) Hage,H-De Smet,K (2260)/corr 1995/Corr 2011}) 17...
Bxf6 18. Nb5 {An overoptimistic move which creates much more problems to White,
rather than Black.} ({The most natural moves in chess are often the best. Here
also -} 18. d6 $5 {though it was tough to calculate at this point, that the
complications will end eventually in a draw.} Bxc3 19. bxc3 Bf5 20. Bf3 Qh4 (
20... Bd3 21. Bd5 Bxf1 22. Qxf1 Qd7 23. Qf6 Re6 24. Qd4 (24. Bxe6 Qxe6 25. Qd4
Ne4 26. d7 Rd8 27. Ne5 f6 $11) 24... Rae8 25. Bxe6 Nxe6 $11) 21. Qd4 Qxd4 22.
cxd4 Ne4 23. d7 Bxd7 24. Ne5 Bc6 25. Nxf7 Kxf7 (25... Rf8 26. Ne5 Nd2 $11) 26.
Bxe4+ $11) 18... a6 19. Nbd6 Rf8 20. b4 Na4 21. Rc1 Nc3 22. Qd2 b5 23. Rxc3 (
23. Nb6 $1 {is some computer tactics, practically impossible to find over the
board.} Qxd6 24. Nxa8 Bf5 25. Rxc3 Bxc3 26. Qxc3 Rxa8 $11) 23... bxc4 24. Ne4
Bxc3 25. Qxc3 f5 26. Nc5 Qd6 27. Bxc4 Kh7 28. Re1 a5 29. a3 axb4 30. axb4 Ra7
31. Ne6 Bxe6 32. Rxe6 Qf4 33. h3 ({Somehow White is still not lost after} 33.
Kg1 $11 {but again, humans can hardly understand this.}) 33... Rfa8 (33... Rc8
$19 34. Qf6 Rg7 35. Re7 Rcg8) 34. Ba6 Rc7 35. Rc6 Rxc6 36. Qxc6 $2 (36. dxc6
$11) 36... Rxa6 $2 (36... Ra7 $19) 37. Qb7+ $11 {and after playing an
excellent game and missing two times a win, Black even managed to lose...} 1-0

