1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. d4 O-O 5. c4 c5 6. d5 d6 7. Nc3 {Fianchetto
System is a positional one, the games here are rarely decided in the opening,
but rather in late middlegame.} Na6 8. O-O Nc7 9. a4 {White better be cautious
about b7-b5, as in some lines Black can even sacrifice a pawn and get an
excellent version of Benko Gambit. For example:} (9. Bf4 $6 {Aimed against
e7-e6 or e7-e5, but allowing strong, typical Benko counterplay. In that case
the bishop on f4 is doing nothing, the pawn on b2 is ooften hanging.} b5 $1 10.
cxb5 Rb8 11. a4 a6 12. Nd2 axb5 13. axb5 Nxb5 14. Nc4 Bd7 15. Qd2 Nd4 16. Ra2
Rb4 $15 {1/2 (50) Urban,K (2489)-Heberla,B (2502) Legnica 2007}) (9. e4 Bg4 10.
h3 (10. a4 Qc8) 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 a6 12. a4 b5 $1 {Again the same motive,
here again White will enjoy the extra pawn only temporarily, his long-term
perspective is just a fight for equality.} 13. axb5 axb5 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. e5 (
15. cxb5 Qa5 16. e5 Nd7 $1 {is the same} ({But not} 16... dxe5 17. d6 exd6 18.
Qc6 {and White is better, as Nikolic proved in an old game against Torre.}))
15... Nd7 $1 16. exd6 exd6 17. cxb5 Qa5 18. Bd2 Nxb5 $15 19. b4 $6 Qxb4 20. Rb1
Nd4 21. Qg4 Ne5 22. Rxb4 Nxg4 23. Rb6 Ne5 24. Bf4 Ra8 (24... g5 $1 $17) 25.
Bxe5 $6 Bxe5 26. f4 Bg7 27. Ne4 Nf5 $17 {0-1 (41) Liptay,L (2410)-Chatalbashev,
B (2537) Balatonlelle 2002}) 9... e5 {After we provoked a2-a4, I like most to
play like in the main line - going into King's Indian type of position. There
are some other plans - with b6,a6,Rb8; with e6 or a6,Rb8 allowing a4-a5 from
White. But my feeling is that in all these cases White's play is easier.} (9...
b6 {was played with the same idea in the following game. It is a good example
how these positions should be played, though,of course, everything is
complicated and both sides have many other possibilities.} 10. e4 e5 11. Ne1
Ng4 (11... Na6 $5) 12. f3 Nh6 13. Be3 f5 14. Qd2 Nf7 15. Nd3 a5 16. Rae1 Na6
17. exf5 gxf5 18. f4 Nb4 19. Nf2 Ra7 (19... Qf6 $5) 20. Nb5 Re7 21. b3 (21.
fxe5 $5 dxe5 22. Nd3) 21... Bd7 22. Kh1 Rfe8 23. fxe5 Rxe5 24. Bf4 (24. Nh3)
24... Rxe1 25. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 26. Qxe1 Qf6 27. Bh3 Bh6 28. Bxh6 Nxh6 29. Qe2 Nf7
30. Nc7 Ne5 31. Kg2 Qg5 32. Kf1 Kf8 33. Nd1 $6 Qc1 $15 {1/2 (48) Malaniuk,V 
(2610)-Fedorov,A (2555) St Petersburg 1996}) 10. dxe6 {White decides to open
up the position and attack on d6, but again, Black has nothing to be afraid of.
} Bxe6 11. Bf4 (11. Qb3 Qe7 12. Rd1 h6 13. Bf4 Rfd8 $13) 11... Bxc4 12. Bxd6
Re8 13. Bxc5 ({Better was} 13. Nd2 $1 Qxd6 14. Nxc4 Qe7 15. Qd6 $1 {enjoying
some pressure, although after} (15. Bxb7 Rad8 16. Qc1 Qe6 17. Ne3 Bh6 {Black
is very active}) 15... Rab8 16. Rfd1 Ng4 17. e3 Ne5 {Black should gradually
equalize.}) 13... Nfd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Nd4 Rc8 ({After} 15... Qc7 $1 {it is
White who risks more} 16. Bxd5 (16. Ba3 Rad8 17. Rc1 Nf4 $15) (16. Bxa7 Rxa7
17. Bxd5 Bxd5 18. Nb5 Qe5 19. Nxa7 Qe4 20. f3 Qe3+ 21. Kg2 Bc4) 16... Bxd5 17.
Nb5 Qxc5 (17... Qc6 $5) 18. Rc1 Bc4 19. b3 $11) 16. Ba3 (16. Bxa7 $1 {looks
too brave} Qa5 17. Nb5 {but the complications might favour White.}) 16... Nb6
17. Nb5 Bxe2 18. Qxd8 Rcxd8 19. Rfe1 Nc4 20. Nc7 Re5 21. f4 Re3 22. Bc5 Bxb2
23. Bxe3 Nxe3 24. Rxe2 Bxa1 25. Rxe3 Bd4 26. Nd5 Bxe3+ 27. Nxe3 Rd4 $15 0-1

