{System with Bd3 and Nge2.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. e4 d6 4. d4 Bg7 5. Bd3 O-O
6. Nge2 c5 7. d5 {The best reaction against this set-up is going straight in a
Modern Benoni type of position.} e6 8. O-O exd5 9. cxd5 Nbd7 {Here the move
order does not matter much - you may start with 9...a6 or 9...Re8 first.} (9...
Re8 {White's choice in this variation is not huge - apart from the main plan
with 10.h3, Ng3 and future f4, he may try also} 10. Bg5 {but this placement of
the bishop is not in harmony with future Ng3, because in that case after h7-h6,
a retreat to h4 is not possible (g6-g5). And the important thing here is that
neither Qd2 nor f2-f4 work well for White -} a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. Qd2 (12. f4 $2
c4 13. Bxc4 Qb6+ 14. Kh1 Ng4 $17) 12... Ne5 13. Bc2 Nc4 14. Qc1 Bd7 15. b3 Na5
16. Qf4 Re5 (16... b5 $15) 17. Qd2 $6 b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. Bf4 Re8 20. Ng3 b4
21. Nce2 Bb5 $17 {0-1 (51) Chatalbashev,B (2548)-Banikas,H (2598) Kallithea
2009}) 10. h3 Re8 11. Ng3 a6 12. a4 {In this line normally White is aiming for
f2-f4 with a future sacrifice e4-e5. When Black takes, the "f" pawn advances
to f5 with e4 square to be occupied by one of the knights. Black must not
allow such scenario,because the pressure on the "f" file, the passed pawn on
d5 and the gloomy looking bishop on g7 would make his life hard.} h5 {This
weakening of the kingside is justified with the need to spoil White's plans.
Black gets ready to chase the knight and apply pressure on e4 pawn. The play
might get double-edged, though.} ({Similar is} 12... Rb8 {,preparing the
standart b5 advance,as Black goes for h7-h5 on the next move. The
complications in the following game worked nice for him -} 13. Be3 h5 14. f4 $6
h4 15. Nge2 b5 $1 16. axb5 axb5 17. e5 b4 18. Nb5 Nxd5 19. Bxg6 Nxe3 20. Bxf7+
Kf8 (20... Kh8 $1 21. Qxd6 (21. Qd3 Nxe5 $1 22. fxe5 Rxe5 $19) 21... Rxb5 22.
Bxe8 Rb6 23. Qd3 Nxf1 $17) 21. Qb3 Rxb5 (21... Re7 22. Qxe3 Rxb5 $17) 22. Bxe8
Qxe8 23. Qxe3 $13 {0-1 (46) Navara,D (2722)-Maximov,D (2479) Pardubice 2011})
13. f4 {Aggressive, but might be slightly premature.} (13. Bg5 {is more
restrained, with complex, approximately equal position.} Qc7 14. Rc1 Nh7 15.
Be3 h4 16. Nge2 Ne5 17. b4 b6 18. a5 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 c4 20. Qc2 bxa5 $11 21. Qa4
$6 Nf6 22. Qxa5 Qxa5 23. bxa5 Nxe4 $15 {0-1 (77) Dumitrache,D (2504)-Smetankin,
S (2455) Avoine 2002}) 13... h4 14. Nh1 c4 $1 15. Bc2 Nc5 16. Nf2 Nh5 17. f5
Ng3 18. Ng4 $1 Ncxe4 $1 {If Black takes the exchange, he will be left with no
active play while his king is vulnerable. In Modern Benoni quite often the
activity is more important than the material gains!} 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. fxg6
fxg6 21. Nh6+ Bxh6 22. Bxh6 Bf5 ({But here it was safe to grab another pawn,
leaving White to prove that his threats are giving him enough compensation.} 
22... Qb6+ 23. Kh2 Qxb2 $17) 23. Qd4 Qc7 24. Kh2 (24. Bxe4 $44) 24... Qh7 25.
Bf4 Qg7 26. Qxg7+ Kxg7 27. Rfc1 $15 1/2-1/2

