{Saemisch (Kapengut) Variation.} 1. d4 d6 ({I shall deal with different move
orders in the next chapter. Generally we will recieve the position from the
game like that:} 1... Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 d6 6. f3 O-O 7.
Bg5 e6 8. Qd2 exd5 9. cxd5) 2. e4 Nf6 3. f3 c5 4. d5 e6 5. c4 exd5 6. cxd5 g6
7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Bg5 {In Modern Benoni positions Black's counterplay is often
connected with pressure on e4 pawn. Sometimes we manage b7-b5 or c5-c4, using
the fact that if White takes that pawn - then he looses the more important one
in the center. In Saemisch by playing f2-f3, White makes sure such things do
not happen. Well, the pawn is protected, but the knight on g1 does not have
useful square and is often seen maneuvering around for quite some time.
Although the positions in this variation are complex, I am convinced that
Black has nothing to be afraid of.} ({Sometimes White starts with Nge2-g3. The
line I propose, though, is universal and it hardly makes any difference here -
we will chase the knight with h7-h5. The following interesting game shows the
main ideas -} 8. Nge2 O-O 9. Bg5 a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Ng3 h6 12. Be3 h5 13. Be2
h4 14. Nf1 Nh7 {The most typical idea for Black - the knight makes path for
f7-f5 break.} 15. Nd2 f5 16. exf5 gxf5 17. f4 h3 $1 18. g3 Qe7 ({White has
more problems after} 18... Re8 $1 19. Bf2 (19. Nc4 $6 Nb6) 19... Qe7 {for
example} 20. Nc4 (20. O-O $4 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Qxe2) 20... b5 21. axb5 Bxc3+ 22.
bxc3 Qe4 23. Kd2 axb5 24. Rxa8 Qxd5+ 25. Kc1 Qxa8 26. Nxd6 Rxe2 27. Qxe2 Qxh1+
28. Be1 {and it is just a miracle he might survive.}) 19. Nc4 Rb8 20. Qd2 $6 (
20. Qd3 $142 $13) 20... Ndf6 (20... Bxc3 $1 21. Qxc3 (21. bxc3 Re8 $17) 21...
b5 22. axb5 axb5 $17) 21. O-O b5 22. axb5 axb5 23. Na5 Re8 24. Nc6 Qxe3+ 25.
Qxe3 Rxe3 26. Nxb8 b4 27. Kf2 Re8 28. Nb5 Ne4+ 29. Kg1 Bxb2 30. Ra7 $13 {1/2 
(46) Elsness,F (2447)-Turov,M (2591) Norway NOR 2015}) 8... O-O 9. Qd2 h6 10.
Be3 (10. Bxh6 Nxe4 $1 11. Nxe4 Qh4+ 12. g3 Qxh6 13. Qxh6 Bxh6 14. Nxd6 Nd7 {is
about equal} (14... Na6)) 10... h5 {In this variation the most important thing
for Black to know is that he must never play Nbd7 before the opponents knight
had already gone to e2. Otherwise White plays Nh3-f2 with better prospects.}
11. Nge2 Nbd7 {Another subtle thing that many players do not know is that
Black better postpone inclusion of the moves a7-a6 and a2-a4 respectively.
Why? See the game!} 12. Nc1 Ne5 {The potential danger of rushing with the
knight to e5 is that White may try to arrange f3-f4. But in that concrete
position Black has enough tactical resources!} 13. h3 Re8 14. Be2 (14. f4 $2 {
is premature due to} Ned7 15. Bd3 b5 $1 {Here, like in the game two moves
later, this move would not be possible if a7-a6 and a2-a4 were included.})
14... Nh7 15. f4 $6 {Tempting, but leading only to trouble.} ({After} 15. O-O
f5 16. Nb3 {the position is complex with many possibilities for both sides. In
our example Black gradually outplayed his opponent -} fxe4 17. Nxe4 h4 18. Rfe1
Bf5 19. Nf2 Qf6 20. Ng4 Bxg4 21. hxg4 g5 22. Rad1 Re7 23. Bf2 Nf8 24. Qc2 Nfg6
25. Nd2 Nf4 26. Ne4 Qg6 27. Bf1 Rae8 28. Bb5 Rf8 29. Bf1 h3 $19 {0-1 (43)
Shishkin,V (2480)-Ionescu,C (2465) Bucharest 2004}) 15... Nd7 16. Nd3 $6 ({
White had to hurry castling, even if it might cost him a pawn.} 16. O-O Bxc3
17. bxc3 Ndf6 $15) 16... b5 (16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nhf6 $17) 17. Nxb5 Ndf6 18.
Nf2 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Rxe4 20. Bd3 Qh4+ (20... Rb4 $17) 21. Kf1 Rb4 22. Rb1 $2 Ba6
$19 23. Nc3 Bxd3+ 24. Qxd3 Re8 25. a3 Rxf4+ 26. Bxf4 Qxf4+ 27. Qf3 Qc4+ 28. Kg1
Ng5 29. Qf1 Qh4 30. Ne2 Ne4 31. Qf4 Bd4+ 0-1

