{Chapter III : Move Orders and Rare Lines  As I mentioned, one of the ideas to
play Late Benoni is that quite often the opponent is not able to use all the
theoretical lines in his repertoire against King's Indian or Modern Benoni. In
our system the main line is far from King's Indian theory and the most
dangerous lines against Modern Benoni - early f4 with Bb5+ and Bf4 with e3 are
not possible here. But when preparing for a certain player, it is good to note
what he plays in these openings, what kind of positions he is familiar with.
Because many players have not even faced in their practice Late Benoni and
probably would like to transpose to a line they already know. Also some of
them might be reluctant even to push d4-d5. That is why over the years, I have
employed practically all move orders - always searching to stage a war on a
unknown for the opponent territory! Sometimes that is very effective strategy,
like in my game with Kortchnoi, sometimes it might just result in going into
some original and tricky positions.} 1. d4 c5 {Quite often I have gone for 1...
g6, but this can be taken into consideration only by players enjoying the Pirc,
like me!} ({The idea behind Black's first move is that if White likes the
positions without d4-d5, like -} 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 (2... c5 3. d5 g6 {also
allows Schmid Benoni} 4. Nc3 {- and we will reach a position from the game}) 3.
c4 ({or} 3. g3 c5 4. c3) ({or} 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2) 3... c5 4. Nc3 {, he can
not go into them here. After 1...c5 either 2.c3 or 2.e3 do not make great
impression. Another idea is that after 2.d5, Black might choose lines without
early Nf6 - more about it in the next part of the chapter.}) 2. d5 (2. dxc5 {
is not dangerous, of course} e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 ({worse is} 3... Bxc5 4. Ne4 {and
White enjoys a small but steady plus}) 4. e4 Nc6 5. f4 Bxc5 6. e5 Nd5 7. Ne4
O-O (7... Qb6 {might be a little better move order} 8. Nxc5 Qxc5) 8. Nf3 ({
Here White should have taken} 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Qd2 Qxc5 10. Nf3) 8... Ne3 9. Qe2
Nb4 10. Bxe3 Bxe3 11. c3 Nd5 12. g3 b5 $1 13. Rd1 Ba6 14. a4 Rb8 15. b4 $6 Qc7
16. a5 Bb7 17. Rd3 Bxf4 18. gxf4 Nxf4 19. Qe3 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 Nxd3+ 21. Bxd3
Qxc3+ 22. Ke2 g6 23. Qf4 Rfc8 $2 $13 {1-0 (31) Mamedyarov,S (2717)
-Chatalbashev,B (2548) Struga 2009} (23... Rbc8 $1 $17)) 2... g6 3. e4 Bg7 4.
Nc3 d6 5. Nf3 Nf6 {This development, without playing c2-c4, is the so-called
Schmid Benoni. Generally it is positional variation, but as we will see in our
games, it can also become rather sharp.} 6. Bb5+ {In my opinion - the only
move that can trouble Black.} ({After} 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O {I consider the best}
e6 {Now the main options are:} 8. h3 (8. Nd2 {The knight goes to the excellent
square in all Benoni position - c4, but we will either exchange it or chase it
from there.} exd5 9. exd5 Nbd7 10. Nc4 Nb6 11. Ne3 Ne8 {Protecting, just in
case, d6 pawn and preparing f7-f5, gaining space at the kingside.} 12. a4 f5
13. a5 Nd7 14. f4 Ndf6 15. Bf3 Bd7 16. Qd3 Nc7 17. Bd2 Re8 18. Rae1 b5 19. axb6
axb6 20. Nc4 Nb5 ({I saw the next strong move, but somehow was not sure of the
evaluation of the final position...} 20... b5 $1 21. Nxd6 c4 22. Nxc4 bxc4 23.
Qxc4 Rb8 $15) 21. Nxb5 Bxb5 22. Bc3 Ba6 $6 (22... Qd7 $13) 23. Re6 Ra7 24. Rfe1
$36 {1-0 (61) Novikov,S (2545)-Chatalbashev,B (2523) Vienna 2013}) (8. dxe6
Bxe6 9. Bf4 d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 {is rather drawish.}) 8... exd5 9.
exd5 Re8 10. Bf4 {Black should be always careful with the pawn on d6,} Na6 11.
Qd2 {but White also has to remember that in this variation his pawn on d5 is
not overly protected.} ({Important line:} 11. Nd2 Nc7 12. Nc4 Ncxd5) 11... Nc7
12. Bg5 $6 Bf5 13. Nh4 Qd7 14. Nxf5 Qxf5 15. g4 $6 Qd7 16. Bf3 h5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6
18. Ne4 Rxe4 (18... Be5 $15) 19. Bxe4 hxg4 20. hxg4 Qxg4+ 21. Bg2 Kg7 22. Rfe1
Rh8 $13 {Like in the previous game, I managed to lose that one also, despite
my better position...Moral: Whatever opening you choose, most important thing
is to play well! 1-0 (40) Mamedov,R (2659)-Chatalbashev,B (2522) Minsk 2014})
6... Bd7 7. a4 O-O 8. O-O Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Na6 11. Bg5 Nc7 12. Bc4 Re8
13. Rad1 Nd7 14. Qg3 a6 15. f4 {There are some other options, but up to this
point it seems to me that both sides have made perhaps the most logical moves.
White has prepared a breakthrough in the center, while Black will
counterattack with b7-b5.} Qb8 (15... Rb8 {desreves attention, in view of the
improvement for White on the next move.} 16. e5 (16. a5 b5 17. axb6 Nxb6 18.
Be2 Nd7 19. b3 Nb5 $13) 16... f6 17. Bh4 b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. Be2 dxe5 20. d6
exd6 21. Rxd6 Qe7 $13) 16. e5 ({The prophylactic} 16. Ra1 {hindering b7-b5
might be best. Probably it would have given White some slight edge in a
dynamic position, but from practical point of view it is an awfully difficult
move - going back to where the rook has been just two moves ago!}) 16... b5 17.
axb5 axb5 18. Be2 b4 19. Ne4 f5 $1 {This nice shot turns the tables in Black's
favour.} 20. Nd2 dxe5 21. Bc4 Nb5 22. Bxb5 $6 (22. Bxe7 Nd6) 22... Qxb5 23.
fxe5 Bxe5 24. Qh4 Bd4+ (24... Bxb2 $142 $19) 25. Kh1 e5 26. dxe6 Rxe6 27. b3
Nf6 $17 0-1

