1. d4 g6 2. e4 Bg7 3. c4 c5 4. d5 d6 {This position can be reached also after
1...c5 first move.} 5. f3 ({I had expected my opponent to go for f2-f3, but
actually on the next move.} 5. Nc3 e6 {Here it is important for Black to know
that} 6. dxe6 Bxe6 7. Nb5 {is not dangerous} ({or} 7. Bf4 Qa5 8. Qb3 Nc6) 7...
a6 $1 8. Nxd6+ Ke7 9. Bg5+ ({After} 9. Nxb7 Qc7 {the knight is trapped} 10. Qb3
Nd7 {with Rb8 next}) 9... f6 10. Bf4 Bh6 $1 11. Bxh6 Nxh6 12. Qd2 Qxd6 13. Qxh6
Nc6 14. Be2 ({better is} 14. Nf3 Nb4 15. Rc1 Rhd8 $1 16. Be2 Nd3+ 17. Bxd3 Qxd3
$36 {although Black is at least equal}) 14... Qd4 15. Qd2 Qxe4 16. Qe3 Qxe3 17.
fxe3 $15 {0-1 (78) Koneru,H (2513)-Kosintseva,T (2451) Elista 2004}) 5... e6 6.
Nc3 exd5 7. cxd5 a6 8. a4 Ne7 {That was the idea of delaying the development
of the knight. As we saw in Saemisch we have to move it from f6 in order make
f7-f5 break possible. Here everything should be OK for Black, as we are saving
some tempos.} ({Although} 8... Nh6 {is at least not worse than the text, from
h6 the knight might go to f7 in future.}) 9. Bd3 Nd7 10. Nge2 O-O 11. O-O f5
12. Nf4 Ne5 13. Be2 Kh8 14. a5 b5 (14... fxe4 {was more precise} 15. fxe4 ({
the difference is that after} 15. Nxe4 Nf5 {the queen is controlling g5 square}
) 15... Ng8) 15. axb6 Qxb6 16. Kh1 fxe4 17. fxe4 {White's strategy is to
restrict the knight on e7, but it is immediately going to f6.} (17. Nxe4 {
instead, might promise him some edge} Nf5 18. Ng5 Nd4 19. Nfe6 $14) 17... Ng8
18. Qc2 Nf6 (18... Rb8) 19. Be3 Qb7 20. Nd3 Nxd3 21. Bxd3 Qe7 22. Bg5 h6 23. e5
dxe5 $6 ({Here I was afraid of the the kingside weaknesses after} 23... hxg5
24. exf6 Bxf6 25. Bxg6 {but actually the position is unclear} Qg7 26. Bd3 Be5)
24. Bxf6 Rxf6 25. Rxf6 Qxf6 26. Rf1 {Now whatever move Black chooses the
bishop on g7 makes a sad impression.} Bf5 27. Bxf5 gxf5 28. Rxf5 Qg6 29. h4 (
29. h3 {was safer}) 29... e4 $1 {Always remember: activity is often of crucial
importance in all Benoni positions. So it is better to give up a pawn, just to
free the bishop.} 30. Qxe4 Rg8 31. Rf4 Qh5 32. Qf3 Qe5 33. Re4 Qb8 34. Qe2 Rf8
{Black's compensation is obvious, though for the engines White has some ways
of improving his position and stands better. But for a human it is not easy
and even Victor the Great collapses in the time trouble.} 35. Re6 $2 Qg3 36.
Re4 $2 Rf2 37. Re8+ Bf8 38. Rxf8+ Rxf8 $19 0-1

