1. d4 g6 2. c4 Bg7 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. e4 e6 6. Nc3 {Another way to make use
of the move order without Nf6 is the case when White goes for an early Nf3.
But if the same position happen with Bd3 instead of Nf3, then the best advice
for Black is to transpose to the Main Line - with 6...Nf6.} exd5 7. cxd5 ({
After} 7. exd5 Ne7 {leads to a very original play. One of the ideas for Black
is future Nf5-d4, but mainly it is the plan with 0-0, h6,g5,f5,Ng6 gaining
space at the kingside. For example} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O h6 {and now the standard
in all other similar lines} 10. Bf4 {is only loosing a tempo} g5) 7... a6 8. a4
Bg4 9. Be2 (9. Qb3 Bxf3 10. Qxb7 Nd7 11. gxf3 Ngf6 {is dangerous for White -
he is far behind in development.}) 9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd7 11. O-O Ne7 ({The
normal move is} 11... Ngf6 {when we reach a theoretical position from Modern
Benoni. I like the following game -} 12. Bf4 Qc7 13. Re1 O-O 14. a5 Rfe8 {
Black's plan is to possibly manage c5-c4,Nc5,Nd7-e5 (or Ne5,Nd7-c5). It is not
easy, but the opponent has to be careful about that - the squares b3 and d3
can be weak.} 15. Na4 {This move prevents that kind of play, but now e4 pawn
becomes the target -} Re7 16. Ra3 Rae8 17. Rae3 Ne5 18. Bxe5 Rxe5 19. Nb6 Nd7
20. Nc4 R5e7 21. R3e2 Ne5 22. Nxe5 Bxe5 23. Qa4 $15 {0-1 (46) Nikcevic,N (2485)
-Kolev,A (2510) Zaragoza 1996 Black is obviously better - huge difference in
the strength of the bishops!}) 12. Bg5 (12. Bf4 {is another way} Ne5 13. Be2
O-O 14. Qd2 f5 15. Bg5 {not really fighting for an advantage} Nf7 16. Bxe7 Qxe7
17. exf5 gxf5 18. Rfe1 Qf6 (18... Qh4 $5) 19. f4 Rae8 $11 20. Bc4 Qd4+ 21. Qxd4
cxd4 22. Na2 $6 Re3 23. Nb4 Rc8 24. b3 $6 a5 25. Nc2 Re4 26. g3 $6 Rxc4 27.
bxc4 d3 28. Na3 d2 {0-1 (28) Jurek,J (2368)-Chatalbashev,B (2596) Imperia 2008}
) 12... h6 13. Bf4 Ne5 14. Be2 O-O 15. Qd2 Kh7 16. Be3 f5 17. f4 Nd7 18. e5 $1
dxe5 19. fxe5 Nxe5 20. d6 N7c6 21. Bxc5 Qa5 22. Ba3 b5 $5 23. axb5 axb5 24.
Bxb5 Nd4 (24... Qb6+ $142 25. Kh1 Nd4 26. d7 Rfd8 27. Be7 Rxa1 28. Rxa1 Rxd7
29. Bxd7 Nb3 30. Qd6 {Black should be able to hold.}) 25. Ba4 ({Somehow White
got scared of all the tricks} 25. Bc5 $1 Ndf3+ (25... Qxa1 26. Bxd4 $16) 26.
gxf3 Qxa1 27. Rxa1 Nxf3+ 28. Kg2 Nxd2 {but it is actually Black who is playing
with fire} 29. d7 $1) 25... Nc4 26. Qd3 Nxa3 27. Rxa3 Qb6 28. Kh1 Qxd6 29. Rd1
Qb4 30. Ra2 Rfd8 31. h3 Ne6 $17 {All the lines with Ne7 are quite an
unexplored territory. Playing them is a bit riskier, although surely
entertaining. Ok, that is why we all love chess!  Conclusion: Late Benoni is
safer than Modern, but as in many lines (apart from the main one)
transpositions happen into it, a good idea is to wake up your inner Tal :)
Remember - Black should always search for activity and initiative! Good luck!}
0-1

